        <p class="pt-6 pb-6 font-body leading-relaxed text-grey-20 dark:text-white">In this example, we define the validation rules and messages in two arrays. The <code>rules</code> array defines the validation rules for each field. For the password field, we use an array to specify both the <code>required</code> rule and our custom <code>PasswordLength</code> rule.</p>

        <p class="pt-6 font-body leading-relaxed text-grey-20 dark:text-white">The <code>messages</code> array defines the custom error messages for each validation rule. Note that we've included a custom message for the built-in <code>min</code> rule as well as for our custom <code>PasswordLength</code> rule.</p>

        <p class="pt-6 font-body leading-relaxed text-grey-20 dark:text-white">Finally, we call the <code>validate</code> method on the request object to perform the validation. If any validation errors occur, Laravel will automatically redirect back to the form with the appropriate error messages.</p>

        <p class="pt-6 font-body leading-relaxed text-grey-20 dark:text-white">Custom validation error messages are an important aspect of user-friendly web application development. With Laravel's powerful validation system, it's easy to customize error messages to provide clear and concise feedback to users.</p>

